On Sunday, the people of Macedonia had their voice heard during a referendum on the change of their country's name for the Republic of North Macedonia. This change would resolve an old dispute of several decades with Greece, which had blocked Macedonia's application for membership of the European Union and NATO.
Greece, one of the provinces of Macedonia, maintains that the name of its northern neighbour represents a right in its territory and opposed its veto to its entry into NATO and the EU.
In June, both governments signed an agreement based on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents said that change would affect the ethical identity of the majority of the Slavic population of Macedonia.
President Gjorge Ivanov announced that he would not vote during the referendum and that a boycott campaign had raised doubts about obtaining a minimum 50% stake required to validate the referendum.
The question of the referendum was as follows: "Are you for membership of NATO and the EU under the terms of the agreement signed with Greece?"
According to the proponents of the change of name, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, this is the price to be paid to join organisations such as the EU and NATO for Macedonia, which have escaped the collapse of Yugoslavia.
"I have come today to vote for the future of my country, for the youth of Macedonia, so that it can live freely under the aegis of the European Union. This means a safer life for each of us," said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
Although the vote was not legally binding, enough members of parliament stated that they would follow the result of the vote to make it decisive.
The change of name would require a two-thirds majority in parliament.
The State Electoral Commission announced that no irregularities had been detected at 1 p.m.
But the participation was only 16%, while it had reached 34% at the same time during the last parliamentary elections in 2016 that had mobilized 66% of the voters enrolled at the end of the poll.
"I have come to vote for my children. Our place is in Europe," says Gjose Tanevski, 62, who voted in the capital, Skopje.
The Macedonian Prime Minister, Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and his son Dushko participated in the referendum and voted for the change of name, in order to open the vote to membership of NATO and the European Union, in Strumica, Macedonia, on September 30, 2018.
In parliament, in Skopje, 54-year-old Vladimir Kavarvarkov prepares a small scene and has seats in front of tents set up by those who boycott the referendum.
"We want to enter the EU and NATO, but we want to enter through the big door," Kavadarkov said.
"We are a poor country, but we have our dignity.
If they don't want us as Macedonia, we can turn to China and Russia and participate in Eurasian integration."
According to Prime Minister Zaev, NATO membership will allow Macedonia to benefit from the necessary investments, and the unemployment rate in the country is above 20%.
"I think a large majority will be in favour, because more than 80% of our citizens want to join the EU and NATO," said Mr Zaev after filing his newsletter.
He added that a "yes" would be a "confirmation of our future".
According to a poll published on Monday by the Macedonian Institute for Policy Research, between 30 and 43 per cent of the voters would intend to participate in the referendum, which is less than the expected participation rate.
Another survey, organized by the Macedonian network Telma, estimated participation to be 57%.
70% of participants intending to vote said they would vote "yes".
