A total of 68% of students who studied foreign languages received the highest score, A.
The data collected from the 74 SCIS member schools show that 72% of students obtained the highest score, A, in Mandarin, as well as 72% of students who studied German, 69% of students who studied French and 63% of students who studied Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as absolutely essential skills for children and young people in the future.
Now languages as subjects are organized as well as science, technology, engineering and mathematics in the programs of independent schools and other schools.
A UK Employment and Skills Commission survey conducted in 2014 shows that among the difficulties employers face in recruiting candidates, 17% are linked to insufficient language skills.
Language skills are therefore increasingly vital in preparing young people for their future careers.
With more job opportunities requiring languages, these skills are essential in our globalised world.
Regardless of his career choice, a person who speaks a second language will benefit from a real benefit in the future thanks to this sustainable skill.
Being able to communicate directly with foreigners will automatically place the multilingual person in front of its competitors.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of 4000 adults living in the United Kingdom, 75% of them did not master enough a foreign language to hold a conversation. French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage (15%).
This is why investing in language learning is important for children today.
By speaking several languages, including those of emerging economies, children will benefit from better chances of finding rewarding employment.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Several of them will focus on classical contemporary languages, while others will teach languages that are considered important for the United Kingdom in 2020, including Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's preferences, several languages will be accessible in independent schools, with specialized personnel in the field.
The Scottish independent schools want to provide a learning environment that will prepare children and give them the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds them.
It is clear that, in a global trading environment, languages are still of vital importance for the future of the country, which must be reflected in education.
Modern languages must be regarded as "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to Scottish youth.
We have to do this.
