The National Trust monitors the secret life of bats
New research in an area of the Scottish Highlands seeks to reveal how bats use the landscape in their food quest.
It is hoped that the observations will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and guide future conservation activities.
The study of researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common and soprano bats as well as long-eared brown bats and Daubenton in the Inverewe Garden in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed at key locations around the property to monitor bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using portable detectors.
A professional sound analysis will determine the frequency of bat screams and the activities of different species.
A habitat map and report will be prepared to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour across the territory.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation advisor for the NTS, hopes that the results will reveal the most important habitat areas for bats and how they are used by each of these species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management such as the creation of grasslands and how best to preserve forests for bats and other associated species.
In Scotland and the United Kingdom, the populations of bats have declined considerably over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development that affect the perch and result in the loss of their habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also represent a risk, as well as paper muzzles and certain chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks of pets.
The bats aren't really blind.
However, given their hunting night habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to identify insects and obstacles on their flight route.
Responsible for the protection of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 large gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, the NTS takes the bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who conduct regular surveys, perch and sometimes rescues.
The organization has also established the first and only Scottish bat reserve on the site of Threave in Dumfries-et-Galloway, which houses eight of the ten Scottish bat species.
David Thompson, the domain manager, claims that the site is the ideal territory for them.
"Here, in Threave, we have an ideal place for bats," he says.
"We have old buildings, many old trees and all the good habitat.
But there is still a lot to learn about bats, so that the work we do here and in other places will help us to better understand what bats need to prosper."
It stresses the importance of verifying the presence of bats before carrying out the maintenance of the properties, because by destroying without wishing to have a single maternity nest, 400 females and children can be killed, or even the disappearance of a whole local population.
The bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, to disturb them, or to destroy their perch.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and about a lot of our species, we don't know what's going on in their populations right now."
