A few essential facts about Palu and Donggala on Sulawesi Island:
Palu is the capital of the central province of Sulawesi, located at the point of a narrow bay on the west coast of Sulawesi Island, with an estimated population of 379,800 in 2017.
The city celebrated its 40th anniversary when the earthquake and tsunami took place.
Donggala is a regency that runs more than 300 km (180 miles) of coastlines to the northwest of Sulawesi Island.
The population of the regency, an administrative region below a province, was estimated to be 299,200 in 2017.
Fisheries and agriculture are the main pillars of the economy of the Central Sulawesi province, and particularly of the Donggala coastal region.
The extraction of nickel is also an important activity in the province, but is mainly located in Morowali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
Palu and Donggala have been affected by tsunamis several times since a century, according to the Indonesian Disaster Reduction Agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
A tsunami also struck the west of Donggala in 1996, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located on the Pacific seismic fire circle and is regularly shaken by earthquakes.
Here are some of the main earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
2004: A major earthquake, which occurred on December 26 on the west coast of the Indonesian province of Aceh, triggered a tsunami in 14 countries, resulting in 226,000 victims on the Indian Ocean Coast, more than half of which occurred in Aceh.
2005: Several violent earthquakes shook the west coast of Sumatra from late March to early April.
A few hundred people died on the island of Nias off Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8 magnitude earthquake reached south Java, Indonesia's most inhabited island, triggering a tsunami that hit the south coast and killed nearly 700 people.
2009: A magnitude 7.6 earthquake shook Padang, the capital of the West Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: A 7.5- magnitude earthquake devastated one of the Mintawai islands off Sumatra and triggered a tsunami of over 10 metres that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A superficial earthquake shook the regency of Pidie Jaya in Aceh, causing destruction and panic, reminding the inhabitants of the devastation caused by the earthquake and the 2004 deadly tsunami.
No tsunamis were caused this time, but more than 100 people were killed by the collapse of buildings.
2018: Major earthquakes shook the Indonesian tourist island of Lombok, killing more than 500 people, mainly on the north side of the island.
The earthquake destroyed several thousand buildings and left thousands of tourists temporarily blocked.
